    body: "If you are part of a same-sex couple who married after the 2015 Obergefell v. Hodges Supreme Court ruling that made marriage equality the law of every state, you have a long list of legal documents that may still treat you as single. Many LGBTQ+ couples had decades of wills, beneficiary forms, deeds, and tax records written under a legal system that refused to recognize their relationship. Those old documents do not update themselves when you get married. If something happens to one spouse before the paperwork catches up, the surviving spouse can face probate fights, denied benefits, lost homes, and family members who suddenly claim the right to make medical decisions or inherit property. Updating the documents is one of the most important things you can do for each other.\n\nThe good news is that the federal government, every state, and almost every private company now treat legal same-sex marriages exactly the same as opposite-sex marriages. Social Security, Medicare, IRS, the Department of Veterans Affairs, and most pensions all recognize your spouse for survivor benefits, tax filing, and beneficiary rights. The harder news is that no agency or company will automatically update your records based on your marriage. You have to file the paperwork yourself, one document at a time, and each one needs a certified copy of your marriage certificate. This guide walks you through every document worth updating, in the order that protects the most money and the most rights first.\n\nStart by gathering five things before you begin. First, your marriage certificate, with at least four certified copies; you can order more from the county clerk where you married, usually for $10 to $25 each. Second, both spouses' Social Security cards and IDs. Third, a list of every bank account, retirement account, pension, life insurance policy, and property deed in either name. Fourth, your most recent will, trust, power of attorney, and healthcare directive, if you have them. Fifth, a notebook to track every change with the date, the agency or company, and the confirmation number. Keep the notebook in a safe place; you will reference it for years.\n\nThe updates fall into four groups: federal benefits and IRS records, state IDs and deeds, financial accounts and beneficiary forms, and estate planning documents. The whole project takes most couples a few months to finish, working a couple of hours a week. You do not need a lawyer for most steps, though one is helpful for wills, trusts, and complicated estates. Free or low-cost legal help is available through SAGE Legal at sageusa.org, Lambda Legal at lambdalegal.org or 1-866-542-8336, and your local LGBTQ+ community center.",
