    body: "Medical records are some of the most personal data anyone can have, and for transgender and nonbinary people, those records can carry information that some patients want to share with every provider and others want to share only with the specialists they trust. A patient's gender identity, chosen name, history of gender-affirming care, hormone therapy, surgical history, and trans status all live in the electronic health record, sometimes for life. Federal HIPAA law gives you strong rights to see, correct, and limit who can access this information, but the rights are only useful if you know how to use them. Many trans and nonbinary older adults grew up before HIPAA existed (passed in 1996), and many were treated by doctors who freely shared sensitive information without consent.\n\nThe stakes are real. A 2023 study by the Williams Institute found that one in five transgender older adults had a healthcare worker share their trans status without permission, often to family members, hospital staff, or insurance companies. Some patients reported being outed at hospitals during emergencies, in nursing homes, by pharmacies, and during routine checkups. The consequences ranged from awkward conversations to outright discrimination, denial of care, and harassment. Older trans patients are especially vulnerable because they may be in skilled nursing facilities, assisted living, or under the care of multiple specialists where every staff member has chart access.\n\nThe good news is that HIPAA, several state privacy laws, and most modern electronic health records systems (Epic, Cerner, Allscripts, athenahealth, NextGen) give patients real tools to control sensitive information. You can request a designation called \"sensitive\" or \"break-the-glass\" protection on specific parts of your chart, which requires a special override before any provider can see it. You can also request that certain information not be shared with specific insurers or family members. You can review your full chart, correct errors, and get a complete list of every person and entity who has viewed your records over the past six years.\n\nThis guide walks through the steps in plain English: how to request a copy of your full medical record, how to mark sensitive sections, how to update your chart with chosen name and pronouns while protecting old records, how to file a HIPAA complaint if your privacy was violated, and how to plan ahead for emergencies, hospitalizations, or end-of-life care. The steps work for any age, but they are especially important for trans and nonbinary older adults who may be juggling care from multiple Medicare providers, hospital systems, pharmacies, and home health agencies.",
