    body: "Planning the end of life is one of the most loving things you can do for the people around you. For LGBTQ+ older adults, the planning carries an extra weight that many straight and cisgender peers never face. Many people in this community have stories of friends who died during the AIDS crisis whose biological families took the body, denied the partner access, refused to use the correct name, and held a funeral that erased who the person really was. Some lost their homes when a parent claimed property despite years of shared life. Some watched chosen family forced out of the hospital room during the final days. The pain of those stories shaped a generation, and many LGBTQ+ elders carry a quiet fear of dying without their wishes honored, their partner protected, and their identity respected.\n\nGood planning prevents almost all of those outcomes. Federal law and almost every state now recognize legal same-sex marriages for hospital visitation, medical decisions, and inheritance. But marriage is only one piece. Unmarried partners, chosen family, ex-spouses, estranged biological relatives, and trans identity all need specific legal documents to be honored. Without those documents, biological family members often have first claim to make decisions, take possession of the body, and direct the funeral, even if they have not spoken to the person in 30 years. The documents are not expensive and most are free or low-cost, but each one must be filled out, signed, and stored properly.\n\nThis guide walks through every document and conversation that protects an LGBTQ+ older adult and their loved ones at the end of life. It covers healthcare directives that name your spouse or chosen family as decision-maker, hospital visitation authorizations, wills that distribute your property as you wish, designations for funeral and burial, instructions for chosen name and pronouns to be used at the funeral, and conversations with the people who will carry out your wishes. The work takes time but is mostly free. Free help is available through SAGE Legal at sageusa.org, Lambda Legal at lambdalegal.org, and your local LGBTQ+ community center. AARP, the American Bar Association, and the National Hospice and Palliative Care Organization all publish free planning packets too.\n\nA good plan grows out of clear conversations with the people who will carry it out. Pick a quiet weekend, gather your spouse or partner if you have one, your closest chosen family, and any biological family who will respect your wishes. Talk openly about what you want at the end of life: where, with whom, with what kind of care, and what the funeral or memorial should look like. Write the answers down. Then turn the answers into legal documents using the steps below. Update the documents every few years and after any major life change.",
