        content: "An advance healthcare directive (sometimes called a living will, healthcare power of attorney, or durable power of attorney for healthcare) names one person to make medical decisions for you if you cannot speak for yourself. This is the single most important document for LGBTQ+ older adults. Without it, state law gives the right to your nearest biological relative by default, which may be a parent, sibling, or adult child who does not know your wishes or respect your spouse or chosen family. Each state has its own free standard form, available at aarp.org/caregiving, your state attorney general's website, or the National Hospice and Palliative Care Organization at caringinfo.org. Fill out the form with your spouse, partner, or chosen family member's name, address, and phone. Name a backup decision-maker. Specify the kind of care you want (full treatment, comfort care, no resuscitation) and your wishes about pain management, organ donation, and where you want to die. Sign in front of a notary or the required number of witnesses, and give copies to your decision-maker, your doctor, your hospital, your spouse, and one trusted friend.",
